D-particle Gas in a 1-D Box 

The result described above,
that the  Liouville theory seems to have only
a single consistent conformal boundary state, suggests that the effective worldline
description of D-particles in 1+1-d string theory is described in terms of the
tachyon mode  only. We will now proceed to analyze the quantum mechanics
of the non-abelian tachyon mode that
lives on the worldline of (a bound state of) many D-particles.
We will assume that the effective action of the  mode is as given in eqn ().


First, however, let us address an apparent
puzzle. Perturbative study (for small
values of the Liouville interaction ) of the open
1+1-d string spectrum reveals that, like its closed string cousin,
the open string tachyon in 1+1-d string theory is not really
"tachyonic" but rather "massless": its perturbative potential
starts out flat, with zero second derivative instead of with a
negative one as in eqn (). Indeed, in general the
presence of open and closed string tachyonic modes can be seen as
a consequence of the Hagendorn growth of the number massive string
states; the 1+1-d model has no massive on-shell degrees of
freedom, and its physical spectrum is therefore free of tachyonic
instabilities. In other words, in the perturbative regime of
small , D-particles in 1+1-d string theory would appear
to be perfectly stable! So how can the action (), with the unstable potential
(), be a correct
effective model?

The justification for () is that its classical
trajectories reproduce the consistent tachyon profiles
(). This reasoning is still perfectly valid in the
1+1-d theory. The implicit assumption leading to the apparent
contradiction is that a D-particle can be independently localized
in the Liouville direction  as well as in . This assumption, however, is
invalidated by the above-described result, that
a D-particle in the 1+1-d theory has
only  as its low energy degree of freedom, and does not have an independent
 position. This suggests that this  position is in fact correlated
with the value of , and it would seem a good guess that small values of , near the top of the
potential , describe a D-particle in the strongly coupled
region near the "Liouville wall," while large values of  (near the flat region
of the potential ) correspond to  values in the weakly coupled
asymptotic region. All this is of course very reminiscent of the holographic
dictionary of the AdS/CFT correspondence, and, more to the point, of its precursor:
the c=1 matrix model.



The  matrix model describes 1+1-d string theory in terms of the
quantum mechanics of a single large  matrix. It has long been recognized,
ever since the D-brane string revolution, that the eigenvalues
of this large  matrix have a likely interpretation as
the positions
of D-particles of a suitable type. Given the above discussion,
it is natural to suspect that the appropriate D-particle is that of
the 1+1-d theory itself. The effective lagrangian describing 
such D-particles is
S() = -   dt  Tr   (
V() 
